1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,780
 - Hello, and welcome to our lecture on SQL.

2
00:00:02,780 --> 00:00:06,940
 So this is a very, very short introduction to SQL.

3
00:00:06,940 --> 00:00:11,380
 I love SQL, I was talking to a student the other day,

4
00:00:11,380 --> 00:00:13,880
 and they were like, SQL's my favorite language.

5
00:00:13,880 --> 00:00:15,260
 And I said, I have to agree

6
00:00:15,260 --> 00:00:18,340
 that SQL is my favorite language, too.

7
00:00:18,340 --> 00:00:21,260
 Because SQL is so beautiful,

8
00:00:21,260 --> 00:00:23,240
 you don't even need to write loops in SQL.

9
00:00:23,240 --> 00:00:25,160
 We write loops in languages like Python

10
00:00:25,160 --> 00:00:27,120
 just because we have to.

11
00:00:27,120 --> 00:00:30,860
 The problem is, is that SQL is just, is perfect,

12
00:00:30,860 --> 00:00:33,300
 but it's not the way we could write something

13
00:00:33,300 --> 00:00:36,120
 as complex as Linux or Python.

14
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:38,700
 And so SQL's not really the way computers think.

15
00:00:38,700 --> 00:00:41,900
 We have these things called database engines.

16
00:00:41,900 --> 00:00:44,580
 And these database engines make things work

17
00:00:44,580 --> 00:00:46,200
 really, really well.

18
00:00:46,200 --> 00:00:49,500
 And so, SQL is a great way to organize data,

19
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:53,340
 but a lot of work has gone into keeping that data organized

20
00:00:53,340 --> 00:00:54,460
 and making it simple.

21
00:00:54,460 --> 00:00:56,940
 So there's a, it's like there's this abstraction,

22
00:00:56,940 --> 00:01:00,360
 and it's a lot of work to make that abstraction work.

23
00:01:00,360 --> 00:01:02,380
 So I want to start out with a little bit of history,

24
00:01:02,380 --> 00:01:04,780
 sort of before databases.

25
00:01:04,780 --> 00:01:09,080
 And you might think, well, before databases,

26
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:09,920
 how could that be?

27
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:11,580
 Well, you know, it's in the old days,

28
00:01:11,580 --> 00:01:15,620
 and if you watch old computer, movies featuring computers,

29
00:01:15,620 --> 00:01:18,960
 you see pictures that have these,

30
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:20,800
 you see pictures that have these tape machines

31
00:01:20,800 --> 00:01:22,220
 in the background, and they're spinning.

32
00:01:22,220 --> 00:01:25,180
 And the spinning of the tape machine is the,

33
00:01:25,180 --> 00:01:28,580
 sort of physical manifestation of computation.

34
00:01:28,580 --> 00:01:31,220
 And it had to do with the fact that in the old days,

35
00:01:31,220 --> 00:01:33,920
 computers did not have enough data

36
00:01:33,920 --> 00:01:37,060
 to store all of their data in the memory or on a disk.

37
00:01:37,060 --> 00:01:39,700
 We didn't even have disks in the early days.

38
00:01:39,700 --> 00:01:42,000
 In the early days, tapes were what we had.

39
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:44,620
 And we used kind of a variation of audio tapes,

40
00:01:44,620 --> 00:01:48,940
 and instead of on audio, they contained data, zeros and ones.

41
00:01:48,940 --> 00:01:50,940
 And so the way things would work in the old days

42
00:01:50,940 --> 00:01:53,540
 so that you could have a database, as it were,

43
00:01:53,540 --> 00:01:57,540
 was the database was all of your data recorded onto a tape.

44
00:01:57,540 --> 00:02:01,780
 And the key thing to a tape is that it was a physical thing,

45
00:02:01,780 --> 00:02:04,500
 and so you had to rewind it and go forwards and backwards.

46
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:07,900
 And most of you probably never even have seen a cassette tape

47
00:02:07,900 --> 00:02:09,800
 or a track tape or a reel-to-reel tape,

48
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:14,600
 but it's a physical, long, thousand-foot piece of plastic,

49
00:02:14,600 --> 00:02:16,300
 and to get the data at the end,

50
00:02:16,300 --> 00:02:18,980
 you had to spin it until you got there.

51
00:02:18,980 --> 00:02:21,340
 And so it wasn't what we call random access,

52
00:02:21,340 --> 00:02:23,220
 which means that in a random access,

53
00:02:23,220 --> 00:02:25,500
 whether it's memory or the disk drive,

54
00:02:25,500 --> 00:02:27,940
 random access allows you to get to any place

55
00:02:27,940 --> 00:02:29,740
 roughly in a fixed amount of time,

56
00:02:29,740 --> 00:02:32,180
 whereas if you're close to something on a tape,

57
00:02:32,180 --> 00:02:33,460
 you can get to it very quickly.

58
00:02:33,460 --> 00:02:35,780
 If you're far away, you gotta go, "Boo!"

59
00:02:35,780 --> 00:02:38,300
 and then wait and then come back.

60
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:43,620
 So this led to a pattern where every night,

61
00:02:43,620 --> 00:02:47,540
 we would take the tape from yesterday's account balances.

62
00:02:47,540 --> 00:02:49,040
 Let's just say we're a bank,

63
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:50,980
 and we're people coming up the window,

64
00:02:50,980 --> 00:02:52,780
 putting in money, taking out money,

65
00:02:52,780 --> 00:02:54,020
 and then what we would do

66
00:02:54,020 --> 00:02:56,100
 is we would put all of the transactions,

67
00:02:56,100 --> 00:02:58,740
 sometimes on physically punched cards,

68
00:02:58,740 --> 00:03:01,080
 and then we would sort them, right?

69
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:03,700
 And let's just say we have 26 accounts,

70
00:03:03,700 --> 00:03:07,300
 and person C shows up with a little,

71
00:03:07,300 --> 00:03:13,000
 adds $10, and person F shows up and subtracts $10,

72
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:14,940
 and et cetera, et cetera.

73
00:03:14,940 --> 00:03:17,260
 And then what we would have at night,

74
00:03:17,260 --> 00:03:18,460
 we would get these all sorted,

75
00:03:18,460 --> 00:03:19,820
 and there were physical machines

76
00:03:19,820 --> 00:03:22,860
 that would actually sort these in the earliest of days.

77
00:03:22,860 --> 00:03:27,860
 And then we would have the old balance A, B, C, D, E, F

78
00:03:27,860 --> 00:03:33,120
 sitting on a tape in order, sorted in order.

79
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:36,540
 And we would start a process after the bank closed

80
00:03:36,540 --> 00:03:41,140
 where we would read the first record off the tape, like A,

81
00:03:41,140 --> 00:03:46,140
 we would read the first transaction off the cards,

82
00:03:46,140 --> 00:03:47,580
 and we would compare them.

83
00:03:47,580 --> 00:03:52,580
 And if the tape was earlier than the transaction or lower,

84
00:03:52,580 --> 00:03:56,060
 we would just copy it, so we'd copy it.

85
00:03:56,060 --> 00:03:58,940
 And then so the B would compare to the C,

86
00:03:58,940 --> 00:04:01,700
 and B would get copied, and then C would come across,

87
00:04:01,700 --> 00:04:03,980
 and then we'd realize that the C data,

88
00:04:03,980 --> 00:04:06,220
 we would have to update the C data

89
00:04:06,220 --> 00:04:09,300
 and add $10 to the balance, and then we'd write that.

90
00:04:09,300 --> 00:04:10,940
 And you'll notice as we're writing this,

91
00:04:10,940 --> 00:04:13,020
 we are sorting, it's in sorted order.

92
00:04:13,020 --> 00:04:15,260
 Then we would copy D, we have nothing for D,

93
00:04:15,260 --> 00:04:16,700
 and it would just get copied.

94
00:04:16,700 --> 00:04:19,060
 We would copy E, we'd have nothing for E,

95
00:04:19,060 --> 00:04:20,340
 and it would just get copied.

96
00:04:20,340 --> 00:04:21,760
 And then we would have, oops,

97
00:04:21,760 --> 00:04:23,460
 forgot to put F on this picture.

98
00:04:23,460 --> 00:04:25,100
 We would have F, and we'd subtract 10,

99
00:04:25,100 --> 00:04:26,100
 and we would copy it.

100
00:04:26,100 --> 00:04:27,380
 And then we would be done.

101
00:04:27,380 --> 00:04:28,820
 We would be done with the kind of stuff

102
00:04:28,820 --> 00:04:31,060
 that we had to do that night.

103
00:04:31,060 --> 00:04:34,140
 And then what we would do is we'd have this new updated data

104
00:04:34,140 --> 00:04:36,580
 that was all sorted in account order,

105
00:04:36,580 --> 00:04:39,740
 and then the next night we would move the tape,

106
00:04:39,740 --> 00:04:41,580
 the new would be the old tape,

107
00:04:41,580 --> 00:04:43,760
 and we would do it over and over and over again.

108
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:47,040
 And sometimes these processes would run for four or five

109
00:04:47,040 --> 00:04:48,580
 hours 'cause the tapes were long,

110
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:50,420
 or it got to be multiple tapes.

111
00:04:50,420 --> 00:04:53,900
 And so a lot of computing was done sort of

112
00:04:53,900 --> 00:04:55,980
 after the banks closed at five o'clock.

113
00:04:55,980 --> 00:04:57,540
 Then a group of people would come in,

114
00:04:57,540 --> 00:04:59,780
 we called them operators, and they would mount these tapes

115
00:04:59,780 --> 00:05:01,740
 and run these jobs, and just sit there

116
00:05:01,740 --> 00:05:04,420
 and watch these tapes spin as the data was being copied

117
00:05:04,420 --> 00:05:05,840
 from one to the other.

118
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:09,740
 And so, yeah, that's pretty cool.

119
00:05:09,740 --> 00:05:12,440
 Thankfully, that's not how we do it anymore.

120
00:05:12,440 --> 00:05:14,580
 The thing that made it so we don't have to do this

121
00:05:14,580 --> 00:05:16,540
 is the invention of disk drives.

122
00:05:16,540 --> 00:05:22,500
 And disk drives are magnetic media, just like tape drives,

123
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:26,100
 but the difference was is they were on these spinning platters.

124
00:05:26,100 --> 00:05:30,340
 And so what you could do is the data was in series

125
00:05:30,340 --> 00:05:32,540
 of concentric circles on these platters,

126
00:05:32,540 --> 00:05:35,860
 and then you had a head that could move in and out rapidly.

127
00:05:35,860 --> 00:05:38,340
 And so the speed at which you could access data

128
00:05:38,340 --> 00:05:40,540
 was a combination with the speed at which the head

129
00:05:40,540 --> 00:05:42,660
 could move to a certain cylinder,

130
00:05:42,660 --> 00:05:45,460
 and you had to wait until the data came around.

131
00:05:45,460 --> 00:05:49,620
 And so sometimes you would have a 5,400 revolution

132
00:05:49,620 --> 00:05:54,220
 per minute, so that means that 5,400, 5,000 times per minute,

133
00:05:54,220 --> 00:05:58,580
 which is 100 times a second, can I get there?

134
00:05:58,580 --> 00:05:59,780
 Yeah, 100 times a second.

135
00:05:59,780 --> 00:06:02,280
 Yeah, 100 times a second.

136
00:06:02,280 --> 00:06:05,500
 100 times a second, you'd wait a hundredth of a second

137
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:08,540
 for it, and so this is way better than waiting

138
00:06:08,540 --> 00:06:11,240
 like a minute and a half, two minutes,

139
00:06:11,240 --> 00:06:13,220
 even 10 minutes to spin up a tape.

140
00:06:13,220 --> 00:06:16,100
 And so the problem was is then we're like,

141
00:06:16,100 --> 00:06:18,420
 okay, now that we have this wonderful technology

142
00:06:18,420 --> 00:06:21,120
 and we can store all of our nightly data on a disk,

143
00:06:21,120 --> 00:06:24,580
 'cause it's enough space, how do we build technology

144
00:06:24,580 --> 00:06:25,940
 to make really good use of this?

145
00:06:25,940 --> 00:06:28,940
 And a lot of research, a lot of computer science,

146
00:06:28,940 --> 00:06:32,820
 a lot of vendor research went into understanding

147
00:06:32,820 --> 00:06:35,380
 how to best use this new disk thing.

148
00:06:35,380 --> 00:06:37,500
 I remember talking to people like,

149
00:06:37,500 --> 00:06:39,260
 'cause we used to use floppy disk works

150
00:06:39,260 --> 00:06:43,100
 where they were much slower, so they didn't go 5,400,

151
00:06:43,100 --> 00:06:46,540
 so it might take a quarter of a second to move the head

152
00:06:46,540 --> 00:06:49,980
 and it might take almost a second to spin it around,

153
00:06:49,980 --> 00:06:52,380
 which was still way faster than 10 minutes, right?

154
00:06:52,380 --> 00:06:54,340
 So it's like about a second to get to anywhere

155
00:06:54,340 --> 00:06:56,180
 on a floppy disk.

156
00:06:56,180 --> 00:06:59,500
 And we would build approaches to storing data

157
00:06:59,500 --> 00:07:01,900
 and we would start with this physical thing

158
00:07:01,900 --> 00:07:03,500
 and you would hear it grunting and moving

159
00:07:03,500 --> 00:07:05,220
 and grunting and moving, and then you would come up

160
00:07:05,220 --> 00:07:06,780
 with a better way to store the data,

161
00:07:06,780 --> 00:07:08,380
 and then it'd grunt and move less

162
00:07:08,380 --> 00:07:09,980
 and your thing would go faster.

163
00:07:09,980 --> 00:07:11,460
 So this was like a research thing.

164
00:07:11,460 --> 00:07:13,620
 It was like, it was good old days

165
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:15,460
 when computers actually made noises

166
00:07:15,460 --> 00:07:18,760
 and you could, it could change your code inside computers.

167
00:07:18,760 --> 00:07:22,120
 And the first thing, of course, we did was just took

168
00:07:22,120 --> 00:07:24,380
 those sequential master updates and put them on,

169
00:07:24,380 --> 00:07:26,280
 but that turned out to not be the best.

170
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:27,880
 And that was sort of the research is,

171
00:07:27,880 --> 00:07:30,640
 not just how can we do what we used to do on data

172
00:07:30,640 --> 00:07:33,420
 that couldn't be randomly accessed

173
00:07:33,420 --> 00:07:36,320
 and instead say, let's take advantage of it.

174
00:07:36,320 --> 00:07:39,060
 And so a lot of research, a lot of vendors,

175
00:07:39,060 --> 00:07:41,700
 there was a lot of very expensive software

176
00:07:41,700 --> 00:07:45,060
 that people bought to say, look, you're a bank

177
00:07:45,060 --> 00:07:49,340
 and you really and truly wanna know how this works.

178
00:07:49,340 --> 00:07:53,060
 And so what happened was is in the 60s and 70s,

179
00:07:53,060 --> 00:07:55,840
 the computer vendors were fighting

180
00:07:55,840 --> 00:07:58,140
 and they would come up with a technique,

181
00:07:58,140 --> 00:08:00,980
 which compared to our current database technique

182
00:08:00,980 --> 00:08:03,940
 was just trivially simple, but it took a lot of work

183
00:08:03,940 --> 00:08:07,420
 back then and they would fight

184
00:08:07,420 --> 00:08:08,700
 with all the other computer vendors.

185
00:08:08,700 --> 00:08:11,300
 And they would say, our index sequential mechanism

186
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:13,560
 is better and vendor two would say,

187
00:08:13,560 --> 00:08:16,040
 our network approach is better.

188
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:17,780
 And then they would sit and they would sort of struggle

189
00:08:17,780 --> 00:08:20,540
 with each other and then the poor customers would be like,

190
00:08:20,540 --> 00:08:22,140
 I don't even know what you're talking about.

191
00:08:22,140 --> 00:08:25,340
 And so then they would just buy the stuff from the vendor

192
00:08:25,340 --> 00:08:28,780
 who took them out to golf or the best lunch

193
00:08:28,780 --> 00:08:30,580
 or took them on a trip to Florida.

194
00:08:30,580 --> 00:08:33,620
 And then they would just adapt to whatever that vendor did.

195
00:08:34,940 --> 00:08:37,740
 And so it was really kind of scary

196
00:08:37,740 --> 00:08:40,380
 because we were moving into a place

197
00:08:40,380 --> 00:08:42,640
 where you were locked into a vendor.

198
00:08:42,640 --> 00:08:45,100
 And then once you're locked into a vendor,

199
00:08:45,100 --> 00:08:45,940
 you're in bad shape.

200
00:08:45,940 --> 00:08:49,700
 And so the US government in particular had a ton of money

201
00:08:49,700 --> 00:08:51,160
 and were buying tons of computers,

202
00:08:51,160 --> 00:08:53,800
 both for normal data processing

203
00:08:53,800 --> 00:08:57,800
 and for strategic things like military stuff.

204
00:08:57,800 --> 00:09:02,160
 And so they were buying tons of computers

205
00:09:02,160 --> 00:09:04,140
 and they knew that these vendors,

206
00:09:04,140 --> 00:09:06,100
 if they got to the point where they locked them

207
00:09:06,100 --> 00:09:07,700
 into a single vendor,

208
00:09:07,700 --> 00:09:10,860
 that the vendor would just be able to dictate the price.

209
00:09:10,860 --> 00:09:14,540
 And so the federal government through NIST,

210
00:09:14,540 --> 00:09:17,480
 the National Institute of Standards and Technology,

211
00:09:17,480 --> 00:09:20,300
 decided that databases needed a standard.

212
00:09:20,300 --> 00:09:23,900
 They needed a way so that we could talk to any database

213
00:09:23,900 --> 00:09:26,180
 from any vendor using the same technique

214
00:09:26,180 --> 00:09:31,640
 and not have to do one vendor.

215
00:09:31,640 --> 00:09:32,700
 And then if you switched vendors,

216
00:09:32,700 --> 00:09:34,420
 you had to completely rewrite your software.

217
00:09:34,420 --> 00:09:35,260
 And so they didn't,

218
00:09:35,260 --> 00:09:39,780
 the NIST didn't specify how this abstraction,

219
00:09:39,780 --> 00:09:41,540
 the standard was going to work.

220
00:09:41,540 --> 00:09:43,220
 They just brought the vendors in and said,

221
00:09:43,220 --> 00:09:45,640
 we're gonna stop using your software

222
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:48,220
 if you don't come up with a standard.

223
00:09:48,220 --> 00:09:50,060
 And it was a perfect time

224
00:09:50,060 --> 00:09:52,220
 because even though the vendors thought they had,

225
00:09:52,220 --> 00:09:54,340
 everything was perfect and wonderful,

226
00:09:54,340 --> 00:09:57,900
 there was a lot of upside.

227
00:09:57,900 --> 00:09:59,740
 And in particular, there was this concept

228
00:09:59,740 --> 00:10:02,020
 of relational databases, which back then

229
00:10:02,020 --> 00:10:04,140
 was more of a mathematical theory

230
00:10:04,140 --> 00:10:05,980
 of a better way to store and retrieve data

231
00:10:05,980 --> 00:10:09,300
 than it was a practically implemented available technology.

232
00:10:09,300 --> 00:10:11,980
 And so SQL, and this is Liz Fong,

233
00:10:11,980 --> 00:10:14,260
 who I went and I did an interview at NIST.

234
00:10:14,260 --> 00:10:15,940
 She talks about the early days.

235
00:10:15,940 --> 00:10:17,340
 It's a great interview.

236
00:10:17,340 --> 00:10:19,900
 The early days of how this SQL standard

237
00:10:19,900 --> 00:10:23,500
 really made so much sense and really fixed the industry

238
00:10:23,500 --> 00:10:25,180
 and got the industry working really nicely.

239
00:10:25,180 --> 00:10:29,440
 And I recommend that you take a look at this video

240
00:10:29,440 --> 00:10:31,180
 just so you can kind of see.

241
00:10:31,180 --> 00:10:34,100
 Now, what SQL basically said was

242
00:10:34,100 --> 00:10:37,260
 is that let's not worry so much

243
00:10:37,260 --> 00:10:39,580
 about where that data is actually on disk

244
00:10:39,580 --> 00:10:41,920
 because the earlier database approaches

245
00:10:41,920 --> 00:10:44,220
 where we programmers would know

246
00:10:44,220 --> 00:10:46,660
 that there was cylinders and positions

247
00:10:46,660 --> 00:10:48,660
 and we would place things in certain ways

248
00:10:48,660 --> 00:10:50,220
 and we would make indexes

249
00:10:50,220 --> 00:10:52,340
 and we would look at the indexes ourselves,

250
00:10:52,340 --> 00:10:53,780
 all kind of different things.

251
00:10:53,780 --> 00:10:56,140
 Or we would read to one place on the disk

252
00:10:56,140 --> 00:10:57,300
 and that would have an address

253
00:10:57,300 --> 00:10:59,700
 of the next place we're supposed to read on the disk.

254
00:10:59,700 --> 00:11:02,500
 And they said, you know what?

255
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:04,500
 Let's not worry so much

256
00:11:04,500 --> 00:11:07,500
 about the physical storage structure on the disk.

257
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:11,500
 But instead, let's come up with a language

258
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:16,500
 by which we can express what we want to read, write,

259
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:17,860
 update and delete on the disk

260
00:11:17,860 --> 00:11:19,820
 and a really simple language.

261
00:11:19,820 --> 00:11:21,380
 And then we can build a piece of software

262
00:11:21,380 --> 00:11:25,060
 that there could be many disk formats underneath that.

263
00:11:25,060 --> 00:11:28,380
 And then we could all sort of just use this language

264
00:11:28,380 --> 00:11:31,100
 and you could buy vendor A and use this language

265
00:11:31,100 --> 00:11:32,380
 and vendor B and use this language.

266
00:11:32,380 --> 00:11:34,680
 And then you could even benchmark it and say,

267
00:11:34,680 --> 00:11:36,420
 here's a bunch of stuff in this language.

268
00:11:36,420 --> 00:11:38,420
 Which vendor can run this faster?

269
00:11:38,420 --> 00:11:42,380
 And so the NIST also had a series of benchmarks,

270
00:11:42,380 --> 00:11:44,820
 TPC or some of the benchmarks.

271
00:11:44,820 --> 00:11:49,980
 And so what they did is they basically made it

272
00:11:49,980 --> 00:11:52,720
 so that this was like a beautiful and simple language.

273
00:11:52,720 --> 00:11:55,820
 And it's what we call SQL, I think at some point

274
00:11:55,820 --> 00:11:58,460
 it was called the Simple Query Language.

275
00:11:58,460 --> 00:12:01,900
 And it is the language that we use to talk to databases.

276
00:12:01,900 --> 00:12:05,780
 And the interesting thing is what SQL allowed us to do

277
00:12:05,780 --> 00:12:08,860
 really in the 60s and 70s when it first came out

278
00:12:08,860 --> 00:12:11,940
 was to talk to the old style databases

279
00:12:11,940 --> 00:12:15,200
 like index sequential and network style databases.

280
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:18,300
 And as this new form called relational databases

281
00:12:18,300 --> 00:12:21,020
 which had like this awesome mathematical underpinning

282
00:12:21,020 --> 00:12:23,320
 of what was implemented badly in the first time,

283
00:12:23,320 --> 00:12:25,880
 we could just say, oh, we're kinda, this is all,

284
00:12:25,880 --> 00:12:28,760
 when the performance of relational databases

285
00:12:28,760 --> 00:12:30,720
 got to the point where it was as good

286
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:34,940
 as the other databases, then we could just switch

287
00:12:34,940 --> 00:12:36,920
 and we could talk the same SQL.

288
00:12:36,920 --> 00:12:40,640
 So it allowed an amazing innovation over a 10

289
00:12:40,640 --> 00:12:44,140
 or even 15 year period where the abstraction

290
00:12:44,140 --> 00:12:48,580
 allowed us to improve databases in a wonderful way

291
00:12:48,580 --> 00:12:52,140
 without really having to change how we as programmers used them.

292
00:12:52,140 --> 00:12:55,940
 Pretty dang awesome, I'll be honest.

293
00:12:55,940 --> 00:12:57,540
 And so I've been talking about this idea

294
00:12:57,540 --> 00:12:59,780
 of relational databases and relational databases,

295
00:12:59,780 --> 00:13:02,400
 and I'll admit that when I first saw relational databases

296
00:13:02,400 --> 00:13:05,500
 in the early 1980s, I'm like, this is crap.

297
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:08,180
 Because again, I could hear floppy disks

298
00:13:08,180 --> 00:13:09,700
 and I knew that we were moving a thing

299
00:13:09,700 --> 00:13:11,700
 and I had so much awareness of what was going on

300
00:13:11,700 --> 00:13:14,060
 and I loved that awareness.

301
00:13:14,060 --> 00:13:16,820
 And the relational databases sort of like hid that,

302
00:13:16,820 --> 00:13:19,940
 hid what was going on behind this layer,

303
00:13:19,940 --> 00:13:22,300
 and it turned out that whenever I used it,

304
00:13:22,300 --> 00:13:25,260
 it was slower 'cause it wasn't yet clever.

305
00:13:25,260 --> 00:13:27,220
 And so relational databases started out

306
00:13:27,220 --> 00:13:29,700
 as a mathematical idea as the theoretical best way

307
00:13:29,700 --> 00:13:33,340
 to represent networks of data with columns and rows

308
00:13:33,340 --> 00:13:34,620
 and connections and joins,

309
00:13:34,620 --> 00:13:36,700
 and we'll talk about all that eventually.

310
00:13:36,700 --> 00:13:42,140
 And it was a beautiful idea and the mathematics was right.

311
00:13:42,140 --> 00:13:45,540
 It just took a long time to get to the point

312
00:13:45,540 --> 00:13:48,740
 where it turned the superior mathematics

313
00:13:48,740 --> 00:13:53,740
 of relational databases worked out better

314
00:13:53,740 --> 00:13:55,940
 than the highly cleverly optimized

315
00:13:55,940 --> 00:13:58,280
 previous generation database systems.

316
00:13:58,280 --> 00:14:01,480
 So there's a lot of common database systems

317
00:14:01,480 --> 00:14:03,540
 that you'll run across.

318
00:14:03,540 --> 00:14:06,740
 Some of them are open source, some of them are commercial.

319
00:14:06,740 --> 00:14:10,380
 PostgreSQL and MySQL are open source.

320
00:14:10,380 --> 00:14:12,300
 PostgreSQL is probably the more intricate

321
00:14:12,300 --> 00:14:13,420
 and complex and rich.

322
00:14:13,420 --> 00:14:16,620
 Oracle is a intricate, complex, and rich database

323
00:14:16,620 --> 00:14:18,660
 that's available for lots and lots of money.

324
00:14:18,660 --> 00:14:22,420
 And Microsoft has a database called SQL Server.

325
00:14:22,420 --> 00:14:25,640
 And all these databases that we're seeing evolved

326
00:14:25,640 --> 00:14:29,220
 in a sense after the SQL spec existed.

327
00:14:29,220 --> 00:14:30,980
 So they just kind of built SQL.

328
00:14:30,980 --> 00:14:34,200
 There was legacy databases that kind of learned SQL.

329
00:14:34,200 --> 00:14:36,460
 And there's lots of other databases.

330
00:14:36,460 --> 00:14:40,180
 SQLite is what we're actually gonna use with this course.

331
00:14:40,180 --> 00:14:43,100
 And it's super cool, super fast,

332
00:14:43,100 --> 00:14:47,260
 and on your cell phone, you probably have 40 copies

333
00:14:47,260 --> 00:14:48,660
 of SQLite, and in your car,

334
00:14:48,660 --> 00:14:50,800
 you probably have 40 copies of SQLite,

335
00:14:50,800 --> 00:14:52,740
 'cause it's a real tiny embedded database.

336
00:14:52,740 --> 00:14:55,900
 It's not really good for production scale,

337
00:14:55,900 --> 00:14:59,140
 when you got 100 users simultaneously hitting a website.

338
00:14:59,140 --> 00:15:02,020
 PostgreSQL, MySQL, or Oracle, or SQL Server

339
00:15:02,020 --> 00:15:05,020
 are really kind of online, multi-processing data,

340
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:07,200
 real multi-processing databases.

341
00:15:07,200 --> 00:15:09,700
 But SQLite is great because it's really simple.

342
00:15:09,700 --> 00:15:11,020
 It stores everything in one file.

343
00:15:11,020 --> 00:15:13,060
 We can move the file around, et cetera.

344
00:15:13,060 --> 00:15:17,580
 So I love SQLite, and in this class, and in this thing,

345
00:15:17,580 --> 00:15:19,220
 we're gonna talk about SQLite,

346
00:15:19,220 --> 00:15:21,980
 but everything we talk about applies

347
00:15:21,980 --> 00:15:24,680
 to all of these different database systems.

348
00:15:24,680 --> 00:15:27,020
 So the first thing that you've gotta do

349
00:15:27,020 --> 00:15:28,980
 when you are gonna work with a database

350
00:15:28,980 --> 00:15:30,660
 is you gotta come up with a contract

351
00:15:30,660 --> 00:15:32,100
 between you and the database

352
00:15:32,100 --> 00:15:34,300
 as to what the shape of the columns are,

353
00:15:34,300 --> 00:15:35,260
 how wide the columns are,

354
00:15:35,260 --> 00:15:37,240
 what kind of data you're gonna store in this,

355
00:15:37,240 --> 00:15:40,860
 and it then informs how the database software

356
00:15:40,860 --> 00:15:43,620
 is going to structure that database, like on the disk.

357
00:15:43,620 --> 00:15:45,260
 And part of what you're doing

358
00:15:45,260 --> 00:15:46,980
 is you're allowing the database software,

359
00:15:46,980 --> 00:15:49,420
 MySQL, or PostgreSQL, or SQLite,

360
00:15:49,420 --> 00:15:51,400
 to super optimize its storage.

361
00:15:51,400 --> 00:15:53,600
 I mean, it's so much smarter than you.

362
00:15:53,600 --> 00:15:56,020
 Something like Oracle, or MySQL, or PostgreSQL

363
00:15:56,020 --> 00:15:59,620
 probably represents a billion dollars, if not more,

364
00:15:59,620 --> 00:16:00,820
 of research and development,

365
00:16:00,820 --> 00:16:02,900
 and about the best way to store and retrieve data.

366
00:16:02,900 --> 00:16:06,680
 And you just don't even need to know any of that.

367
00:16:06,680 --> 00:16:09,460
 You just say, look, I'm gonna have these columns,

368
00:16:09,460 --> 00:16:11,220
 it's gonna have 100 characters of text,

369
00:16:11,220 --> 00:16:12,180
 then I'm gonna have an integer,

370
00:16:12,180 --> 00:16:13,280
 and then a floating point number,

371
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:15,140
 then 3,000 characters of text,

372
00:16:15,140 --> 00:16:17,820
 and you worry about all that detail.

373
00:16:17,820 --> 00:16:20,100
 But the key is, is if you just say,

374
00:16:20,100 --> 00:16:22,220
 ah, I'll store anything I want,

375
00:16:22,220 --> 00:16:23,580
 then it can't optimize.

376
00:16:23,580 --> 00:16:25,540
 And so there's this thing where you have to

377
00:16:25,540 --> 00:16:27,720
 make a contract at the beginning and say,

378
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:30,340
 this is exactly how I'm gonna lay out the data

379
00:16:30,340 --> 00:16:32,220
 as I talk to the database system,

380
00:16:32,220 --> 00:16:36,020
 and then you can figure out how to lay out the data

381
00:16:36,020 --> 00:16:37,620
 in the actual disk.

382
00:16:37,620 --> 00:16:40,700
 And so that's called the schema, or the database model.

383
00:16:40,700 --> 00:16:44,460
 And building a database model is itself a cool thing.

384
00:16:44,460 --> 00:16:48,140
 So if you're given building a complex application,

385
00:16:48,140 --> 00:16:49,980
 you have these models, and they have connections,

386
00:16:49,980 --> 00:16:52,620
 and we'll eventually talk about all that stuff.

387
00:16:52,620 --> 00:16:54,900
 But it's a critical thing to say that that's a contract

388
00:16:54,900 --> 00:16:56,740
 between you and the database software,

389
00:16:56,740 --> 00:16:59,420
 so the database software can optimize

390
00:16:59,420 --> 00:17:00,500
 the storage of the database.

391
00:17:00,500 --> 00:17:03,860
 Now once you have given the schema,

392
00:17:03,860 --> 00:17:07,780
 then you can write queries that depend on that schema.

393
00:17:07,780 --> 00:17:09,140
 So you might have a column called email

394
00:17:09,140 --> 00:17:10,380
 and a column called name.

395
00:17:10,380 --> 00:17:12,980
 And then you can insert data into the database

396
00:17:12,980 --> 00:17:13,900
 using that schema.

397
00:17:13,900 --> 00:17:15,940
 You can retrieve data using the schema.

398
00:17:15,940 --> 00:17:17,780
 You can change data sort of somewhere

399
00:17:17,780 --> 00:17:19,300
 deep inside the database.

400
00:17:19,300 --> 00:17:21,460
 And then you can delete data.

